"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"BAAs should permit termination when a cure is not feasible, mirroring HHS's expected drafting.","id":"BAA-012-s1-0","recommendation":"Add language allowing termination if cure is infeasible or if BA fails to cure within a reasonable period.","rule_id":"BAA-012","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"hipaa-45-c-f-r-164-504-e-2-iii-","license":"Public domain (US government work)","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"45 C.F.R. § 164.504(e)(2)(iii)","source_url":"https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-45"}],"title":"No 'cure infeasible' termination right"},{"description":"No definition or HIPAA cross-reference for PHI or ePHI was found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"Section 160.103 defines PHI and ePHI. Drafters should either define these terms locally or incorporate the HIPAA definition by reference.","id":"BAA-028-s1-0","recommendation":"Add a definitions clause that incorporates 'Protected Health Information' and 'electronic PHI' as defined at 45 CFR § 160.103.","rule_id":"BAA-028","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"hipaa-45-c-f-r-160-103-definitions-","license":"Public domain (US government work)","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"45 C.F.R. § 160.103 (Definitions)","source_url":"https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-45"}],"title":"PHI / ePHI definition missing"},{"description":"No clause was found referencing BA's sanctions policy for workforce HIPAA violations.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"Section 164.308(a)(1)(ii)(C) requires workforce sanctions for HIPAA violations.","id":"BAA-034-s1-0","recommendation":"Add a sanctions / discipline clause noting that BA maintains a written sanctions policy.","rule_id":"BAA-034","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"hipaa-45-c-f-r-164-308-a-1-ii-c-","license":"Public domain (US government work)","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"45 C.F.R. § 164.308(a)(1)(ii)(C)","source_url":"https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-45"}],"title":"Sanctions / personnel discipline policy not referenced"},{"description":"No term / duration clause was detected.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"BAAs should state how long the agreement is in effect, including renewal handling.","id":"BAA-038-s1-0","recommendation":"Add a 'Term' clause specifying initial term and renewal.","rule_id":"BAA-038","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"hipaa-45-c-f-r-164-504-e-","license":"Public domain (US government work)","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"45 C.F.R. § 164.504(e)","source_url":"https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-45"}],"title":"Term / duration clause missing"},{"description":"No notice clause was detected.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"A notice clause anchors how breach notifications and other formal communications travel between the parties.","id":"BAA-040-s1-0","recommendation":"Add a notice clause naming the methods (email, certified mail), addresses, and timing requirements.","rule_id":"BAA-040","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"hipaa-45-c-f-r-164-410-c-content-of-notification-","license":"Public domain (US government work)","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"45 C.F.R. § 164.410(c) (content of notification)","source_url":"https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-45"}],"title":"Notice clause missing"},{"description":"The contract does not allocate ownership of intellectual property.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no IP-ownership clause)"},"explanation":"Without an IP-ownership clause, default copyright and patent rules apply: under 17 U.S.C. § 201, copyright vests in the author/employee unless work-for-hire or assignment applies.","id":"IPDATA-001-s1-0","rule_id":"IPDATA-001","rule_version":"1.1.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"stat-17-usc-101","license":"Public domain (US government work)","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-11T00:00:00Z","source":"17 U.S.C. § 101 — Definitions (work made for hire)","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/17/101"},{"id":"stat-17-usc-201","license":"Public domain (US government work)","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-11T00:00:00Z","source":"17 U.S.C. § 201","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/17/201"}],"title":"No IP-ownership clause detected"},{"description":"Neither 'indemnify' nor 'hold harmless' appears in the document.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no indemnification language)"},"explanation":"Most commercial contracts allocate risk through an indemnification clause. The absence leaves the parties to default tort and contract law for any third-party claims.","id":"RISK-001-s1-0","rule_id":"RISK-001","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"No indemnification clause detected"},{"description":"Vaulytica did not find a limitation-of-liability clause.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no LoL clause)"},"explanation":"Without a limitation-of-liability clause, exposure is bounded only by what the parties can prove in damages. Most commercial contracts cap liability.","id":"RISK-005-s1-0","rule_id":"RISK-005","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"No limitation-of-liability clause detected"},{"description":"Used but not defined: Master Services Agreement, Protected Health Information, Security Rule.","document_position":586,"excerpt":{"end_offset":611,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":586,"text":"Master Services Agreement"},"explanation":"Title-Case phrases in a contract usually signal a defined term. When they aren't defined, readers must guess at the intended meaning. Either define them or use lowercase if the term is intended in its ordinary sense.","id":"STRUCT-006-s1-586","recommendation":"Add a definition for each genuinely defined term, or change the casing if the phrase is being used in its ordinary sense.","rule_id":"STRUCT-006","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"Undefined Title-Case terms: 3"},{"description":"The contract does not state a path to terminate for material breach.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no for-cause termination)"},"explanation":"Without a for-cause termination path, parties must rely on common-law material-breach doctrines, which are jurisdiction-dependent.","id":"TERM-002-s1-0","rule_id":"TERM-002","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"No termination-for-cause clause detected"},{"description":"The document does not state where disputes must be brought.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no venue clause)"},"explanation":"Without a venue clause, default venue rules apply (in federal court, 28 U.S.C. § 1391). A clear forum-selection clause avoids ambiguity.","id":"CHOICE-003-s1-0","rule_id":"CHOICE-003","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[{"id":"stat-28-usc-1391","license":"Public domain (US government work)","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-11T00:00:00Z","source":"28 U.S.C. § 1391 (venue generally)","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/28/1391"}],"title":"No venue / forum clause detected"},{"description":"Only business associate bears this typically-mutual obligation.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"confidentiality obligation"},"explanation":"Obligations like confidentiality, indemnity, and representations are usually mutual. A one-sided version is sometimes intentional but worth confirming.","id":"OBLI-002-s1-0","rule_id":"OBLI-002","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Asymmetric confidentiality obligation"},{"description":"Business Associate shall not use or disclose Protected Health Information other than as permitted or required by this BA","document_position":918,"excerpt":{"end_offset":1063,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":918,"text":"Business Associate shall not use or disclose Protected Health Information other than as permitted or required by this BAA or as required by law."},"explanation":"Negative covenants restrict what a party may do. Surfacing them collectively makes it easier to check they are intended and consistent with the overall deal.","id":"OBLI-005-s1-918","rule_id":"OBLI-005","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Negative covenants: 1"},{"description":"The contract uses \"reasonable efforts\" without defining it.","document_position":3506,"excerpt":{"end_offset":3524,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":3506,"text":"ion from Covered Entity, make reasonable efforts to limit such use or disclosure to the minimum necessary to accomplish the intended purpose."},"explanation":"Efforts-standard phrases carry different obligation strengths in commercial drafting. *Bloor v. Falstaff* (2d Cir. 1979) and its progeny treat `best efforts` as the most demanding, `commercially reasonable efforts` as the middle term, and `reasonable efforts` as the weakest — but without an in-document definition, the parties can dispute which standard applies and what conduct satisfies it.","id":"OBLI-008-s1-3506","recommendation":"Either delete the qualifier (let the obligation be absolute) or add an explicit definition of \"reasonable efforts\" — typically a list of required actions (\"including obtaining all consents, devoting professional staff, and absorbing reasonable costs\") plus carve-outs (\"but not requiring litigation, financial harm, etc.\").","rule_id":"OBLI-008","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Efforts standard \"reasonable efforts\" undefined"},{"description":"Provisions are stated to survive termination.","document_position":5195,"excerpt":{"end_offset":5214,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":5195,"text":"Term. This BAA shall be co-terminous with the Master Services Agreement, except that the obligations to return or destroy Protected Health Information shall survive termination of this Agreement."},"explanation":"A survival clause names the obligations that outlast termination — typically confidentiality, indemnity, payment obligations accrued before termination, and choice of law.","id":"TEMP-006-s1-5195","rule_id":"TEMP-006","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Survival clause present"},{"description":"Survival clause does not appear to include: confidentiality, indemnity, payment, governing law.","document_position":5195,"excerpt":{"end_offset":5214,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":5195,"text":"Term. This BAA shall be co-terminous with the Master Services Agreement, except that the obligations to return or destroy Protected Health Information shall survive termination of this Agreement."},"explanation":"Typical surviving obligations include confidentiality, indemnity, accrued payment obligations, and governing law. Missing any of these is common and worth confirming.","id":"TEMP-007-s1-5195","rule_id":"TEMP-007","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Survival list may be missing categories: confidentiality, indemnity, payment, governing law"},{"description":"Upon termination of this BAA for any reason, Business Associate shall return","document_position":2873,"excerpt":{"end_offset":2949,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":2873,"text":"Return or Destruction. Upon termination of this BAA for any reason, Business Associate shall return to Covered Entity or destroy all Protected Health Information received from or created or received by Business Associate on behalf of Covered Entity. If return or destruction is in"},"explanation":"Post-termination obligations typically include return or destruction of confidential materials, deletion of data, and a certificate of destruction.","id":"TERM-007-s1-2873","rule_id":"TERM-007","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Post-termination obligations enumerated"}],"playbook_id":"baa","playbook_match_confidence":1,"playbook_match_reasoning":"forced via sidecar to baa","result_hash":"e465428ed759c2ea761034de0302baa554e79db5e023660c113d8dfa9cb8da12","source_file":{"name":"baa-missing-phi-definition-fail.txt","sha256":"bd9859001fe807329f88c24023e5531189b3a5d6afbfcad97be6fbbbcb815a6b","size_bytes":1},"version":"9.41.0"}